TY  - JOUR
T1  - Event Studies In Management Research: Theoretical And Empirical Issues
AU  - McWilliams, Abagail
AU  - Siegel, Donald
Y1  - 1997/06/01
PY  - 1997
DA  - 1997/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/257056
DO  - 10.5465/257056
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 626
EP  - 657
VL  - 40
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - We examined the use of event studies in management research and found that there was inadequate attention paid to theoretical and research design issues. This lack of attention may lead to false inferences regarding the significance of the events and the validity of the theories being tested. To illustrate the extent of this problem, we attempted to replicate three recent studies. To guide authors and reviewers, we out-line procedures for appropriate use of the event study method.
AB  - We examined the use of event studies in management research and found that there was inadequate attention paid to theoretical and research design issues. This lack of attention may lead to false inferences regarding the significance of the events and the validity of the theories being tested. To illustrate the extent of this problem, we attempted to replicate three recent studies. To guide authors and reviewers, we out-line procedures for appropriate use of the event study method.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/257056
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/257056
Y2  - 2026/04/24
