TY  - JOUR
T1  - Corporate Social Performance And Organizational Attractiveness To Prospective Employees
AU  - Turban, Daniel B.
AU  - Greening, Daniel W.
Y1  - 1997/06/01
PY  - 1997
DA  - 1997/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/257057
DO  - 10.5465/257057
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 658
EP  - 672
VL  - 40
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Drawing on propositions from social identity theory and signaling theory, we hypothesized that firms' corporate social performance (CSP) is related positively to their reputations and to their attractiveness as employers. Results indicate that independent ratings of CSP are related to firms' reputations and attractiveness as employers, suggesting that a firm's CSP may provide a competitive advantage in attracting applicants. Such results add to the growing literature suggesting that CSP may provide firms with competitive advantages.
AB  - Drawing on propositions from social identity theory and signaling theory, we hypothesized that firms' corporate social performance (CSP) is related positively to their reputations and to their attractiveness as employers. Results indicate that independent ratings of CSP are related to firms' reputations and attractiveness as employers, suggesting that a firm's CSP may provide a competitive advantage in attracting applicants. Such results add to the growing literature suggesting that CSP may provide firms with competitive advantages.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/257057
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/257057
Y2  - 2026/04/24
