TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Affirmative Action Stigma Of Incompetence: Effects Of Performance Information Ambiguity
AU  - Heilman, Madeline E.
AU  - Block, Caryn J.
AU  - Stathatos, Peter
Y1  - 1997/06/01
PY  - 1997
DA  - 1997/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/257055
DO  - 10.5465/257055
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 603
EP  - 625
VL  - 40
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - In two studies, 264 male and female managers reviewed information about the job performance of a person portrayed as either a man or a woman and, if a woman, as either an affirmative action hire or not. As expected, subjects rated female affirmative action hires as less competent and recommended smaller salary increases for them than for men and women not associated with affirmative action. This pattern held even when disconfirming performance information was provided if that information was ambiguous either with regard to degree of success (Study 1) or with regard to who was responsible for the success (Study 2).
AB  - In two studies, 264 male and female managers reviewed information about the job performance of a person portrayed as either a man or a woman and, if a woman, as either an affirmative action hire or not. As expected, subjects rated female affirmative action hires as less competent and recommended smaller salary increases for them than for men and women not associated with affirmative action. This pattern held even when disconfirming performance information was provided if that information was ambiguous either with regard to degree of success (Study 1) or with regard to who was responsible for the success (Study 2).
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/257055
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/257055
Y2  - 2026/04/24
